                            <cell right="medium"><m>1</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell right="medium"><m>2</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell right="medium"><m>3</m></cell>
                            <cell><m></m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell right="medium"><m>4</m></cell>
                            <cell><m></m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell right="medium"><m>5</m></cell>
                            <cell><m></m></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular> -->
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                      Write down your answer.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    Look at your answer: 
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Is it a whole number?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Or does it remain as a square root?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        If your answer is not exact (for example <m>\sqrt{20}</m>, try to simplify it using a factor tree.

                       Example:<m>\sqrt{20} = \sqrt{2\times10} = \sqrt{2\times 2\times5} = 2\sqrt5 </m>
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Compare your findings with other groups
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>        
        </statement>
        
    </activity> 
    <insight>
        <p>
            Simplifying irrational numbers means rewriting a  (root) in its simplest form by removing perfect square factors from inside the root.
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Product Rule:</alert> 
                         When a square root contains a product, it can be split:
                         <m>\sqrt{ab}= \sqrt{a}\times \sqrt{b}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                      <alert> Quotient Rule:</alert> 
                         A square root of a fraction can be split:
                   <m>\sqrt{\frac{a}{b}}</m>
                   <m>=\frac{\sqrt{a}}{\sqrt{b}}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Extracting Perfect Squares:</alert>
                        Always look for perfect square factors inside the root:
                        Example:
                            <m>\sqrt{18}=\sqrt{9\times 2}
                              =3\sqrt{2} </m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Simplifying Coefficients:</alert>
                        Numbers outside the root multiply normally
                        Example;
                        <m>=3\sqrt{20} =3\times 2\sqrt{5}
                          = 6\sqrt{5} </m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Adding and Subtracting irrational numbers:</alert>
                        You can only add or subtract like surds (same root inside).
                        Example;
                        <m>=2\sqrt{3}+ 5\sqrt{3}
                        =7\sqrt{3} </m>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </insight>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Simplify:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\sqrt{45}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\sqrt{72}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\sqrt{48}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>3\sqrt{20}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol> 
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>45 = 9 \times 5</m>   Therefore;
                        </p>
                                                <p>
                            <me>\sqrt{45}= \sqrt{9\times5}</me>
                            
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <me>=\sqrt{9}\times \sqrt{5} </me>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <me>=3\sqrt{5}</me>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\sqrt{72}</m>
                            <p>
                                <m>\sqrt{36\times2}</m>
                                <m>=\sqrt{36}\times \sqrt{2} </m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>=6\sqrt{2}</m>
                            </p>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\sqrt{48}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>\sqrt{16\times 3}</m>
                            <m>=\sqrt{16}\times \sqrt{3} </m>
                        </p>
                        <m>=4\sqrt{3}</m>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                             <m>3\sqrt{20}</m>
                             <p>
                                First simplify <m>\sqrt{20}</m>:
                                <p>
                                    <m>\sqrt{20}=\sqrt{4\times5}</m>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>=\sqrt{4}\times\sqrt{5}</m>
                                        <p>
                                           <m>=2\sqrt{5}</m> 
                                        </p>
                                        <p>
                                            Therefore:<m>3\sqrt{20}</m>
                                            <p>
                                                <m> =3\times 2\sqrt{5}</m>
                                                <p>
                                                    <m>=6\sqrt{5}</m>
                                                </p>
                                            </p>
                                        </p>
                                    </p>
                                </p>
                             </p>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
             <li>
                <p>
                    A square garden has area 50 m². Find the side length in simplest  form.
                </p>
             </li>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>A=\text{s}^{2}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>50=\text{s}^{2}</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>\sqrt{50}=\sqrt{\text{s}^{2}}</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>=\sqrt{25\times2}</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>=\sqrt{25}\times{2}</me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>=5\sqrt{2} m </me>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The diagonal of a rectangle is <m>\sqrt{98}</m>cm. Simplify the length.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A square section of a playground has an area of 200 m².
                    Find the exact side length in simplest form.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A classroom is build in square shape and has a side length of <m>\sqrt{20}</m>cm.
                    If the length is doubled, express the new length in simplest form.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A square notice board has a side length of <m>\sqrt{27}</m>cm.
                    If two such sides are placed end to end, find the total length in simplest form.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>
        
